Starting in v6.0, the MongoDB [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith) aggregation stage
supports [$search](pipe.$search) inside the [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith)
`pipeline` option. Using [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith), you can combine
[$search](pipe.$search) results from multiple collections in the same
database in the result set.

> **Warning:** Queries using [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith) with [$search](pipe.$search) in the
> sub-pipeline might fail during an upgrade from a replica set to a
> sharded cluster running MongoDB v7.0 if the collection is not spread
> across multiple shards. To mitigate this, deploy more than one shard
> on your cluster and shard the collection such that multiple chunks
> are spread across multiple shards.

This tutorial demonstrates how to run a [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith) query
with [$search](pipe.$search) against the `companies` and `inspections`
collections in the `sample_training` database. It takes you through
the following steps:

- Create a default MongoDB Search index on the `companies` and `inspections`
  collections in the `sample_training` database.

- Run a [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith) query with [$search](pipe.$search) to perform
  a union of companies with `mobile` in their name from both the
  `companies` and `inspections` collections.

> **Note:** To run a [$unionWith](manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unionWith) query with [$search](pipe.$search), your
> cluster must run MongoDB v6.0 or higher. To upgrade your MongoDB version,
> see [upgrade your cluster to MongoDB 8.0](upgrade-major-MongoDB-version).

